SIMPLE: high-pressure
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: High-pressure
<hw>High"-pres`sure</hw> <pr>(?; 135)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Having or involving a pressure greatly exceeding that of the
atmosphere; -- said of steam, air, water, etc., and of steam, air, or
hydraulic engines, water wheels, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: Urgent; intense; <as>as, a
<ex>high-pressure</ex> business or social life</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Using intense psychological pressure or other
incentives to convince others to do things; aggressively persistent;
<as>as, <ex>high-pressure</ex> salesmen; <ex>high-pressure</ex>
tactics</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>High-pressure engine</b></col>, <cd>an engine in which
steam at high pressure is used. It may be either a condensing or a
noncondensing engine. Formerly the term was used only of the latter. See
<er>Steam engine</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>High priest</ent>⟦br⟧
